  "text": "The RBAC verb handling in Kubernetes spans multiple layers:\n\n1. **Verb definitions**: The canonical set of RBAC verbs is defined in `api/rbac/v1/types.go` (VerbAll=\"*\") and `pkg/apis/rbac/types.go` (internal types). The bootstrap policy in `bootstrappolicy/policy.go` defines Read=[get,list,watch], Write=[create,update,patch,delete,deletecollection], ReadWrite=both combined.\n\n2. **HTTP-to-verb mapping**: `requestinfo.go:NewRequestInfo()` maps HTTP methods to kube verbs (POST\u2192create, GET/HEAD\u2192get, PUT\u2192update, PATCH\u2192patch, DELETE\u2192delete), then refines: nameless GET\u2192list/watch, nameless DELETE\u2192deletecollection. Special path verbs include proxy and watch.\n\n3. **API handler registration**: `installer.go:registerResourceHandlers()` builds action lists (GET, LIST, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, DELETECOLLECTION, WATCH, WATCHLIST, CONNECT) gated by storage interface capabilities (rest.Getter, rest.Lister, etc.). The `toDiscoveryKubeVerb` map translates these to discovery kube verbs: get, list, create, update, patch, delete, deletecollection, watch, proxy.\n\n4. **Authorization enforcement**: `filters/authorization.go:WithAuthorization()` extracts attributes via `GetAuthorizerAttributes()` (verb from RequestInfo) and calls `Authorize()`. The RBAC authorizer in `rbac.go` delegates to `VisitRulesFor()` in `rule.go`, which resolves Role/ClusterRole bindings and checks each PolicyRule via `RuleAllows()` \u2192 `VerbMatches()` (evaluation_helpers.go).\n\n5. **Verb validation**: `kubectl create role` defines `validResourceVerbs` including all 8 standard verbs plus proxy, use, bind, escalate, impersonate. The `Covers()` function in `policy_comparator.go` validates RBAC rule coverage including verb matching via VerbAll wildcard.",
